Visa Approval Facilitation

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective¶

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired the firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist at EasyVisa have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • case_id: ID of each visa application
  • continent: Information of continent the employee
  • education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  • has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  • requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  • no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  • yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  • region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.
  • prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.
  • unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
  • full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full Time Position; N = Part Time Position
  • case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

Note: This is a sample solution for the project. Projects will NOT be graded on the basis of how well the submission matches this sample solution. Projects will be graded on the basis of the rubric only.¶

# Reusable code  
# Visualize both the histogram and box plot for each variable to gain clear insights into the data distribution and characteristics.

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# Reusable code  
# Visualize the bar plot for each variable to gain clear insights into the data characteristics.

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 6))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 6))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# Step 1: Crosstab with percentage of case_status within each education level
education_impact = pd.crosstab(
    df_visa["education_of_employee"],
    df_visa["case_status"],
    normalize='index'
) * 100

education_impact = education_impact.round(2)
education_impact.columns.name = "Case Status"
education_impact.index.name = "Education Level"

print("Crosstab: Percentage of Visa Case Status by Education Level")
print(education_impact)

# Step 2: Prepare Certified and Denied rates as a new DataFrame for plotting
plot_data = education_impact[["Certified", "Denied"]].copy()
plot_data = plot_data.sort_values(by="Certified", ascending=False)

# Step 3: Grouped bar plot (side-by-side)
ax = plot_data.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(10, 6), color=['skyblue', 'lightcoral'])

# Add percentage labels on top of each bar
for container in ax.containers:
    ax.bar_label(container, fmt='%.1f%%', label_type='edge', fontsize=9)

# Final plot formatting
plt.title('Visa Approval vs Denial Rate by Education Level')
plt.ylabel('Percentage (%)')
plt.xlabel('Education Level')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.ylim(0, 100)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.legend(title='Case Status')
plt.show()

def distribution_plot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Plots histogram and boxplots of a predictor variable grouped by target.

    Parameters:
    - data: pandas DataFrame
    - predictor: str, column name for the predictor variable
    - target: str, column name for the target variable
    """
    
    target_vals = data[target].unique()
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    # Histograms for each target value
    colors = ['teal', 'orange']
    for i, val in enumerate(target_vals[:2]):
        sns.histplot(
            data=data[data[target] == val],
            x=predictor,
            kde=True,
            stat='density',
            color=colors[i % len(colors)],
            ax=axs[0, i]
        )
        axs[0, i].set_title(f"Distribution for {target} = {val}")

    # Boxplots
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette='Set2')
    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot by Target")

    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 1], showfliers=False, palette='Set2')
    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (No Outliers) by Target")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Model evaluation criterion¶

Understanding Wrong Predictions in Visa Approval Modeling¶

When our model predicts whether a visa application will be Certified or Denied, it can make two types of incorrect predictions:

  1. False Positive (Type I Error)

    • The model predicts: Certified
    • Reality: Denied
    • Risk: A visa is wrongly approved.

  2. False Negative (Type II Error)

    • The model predicts: Denied
    • Reality: Certified
    • Risk: A qualified person is wrongly rejected, and the U.S. loses a skilled worker who could contribute to the economy.

Which Case Is More Important?¶

Both types of errors are important:

  • Certifying someone who should be denied takes away job opportunities from eligible local workers.
  • Denying someone who should be certified leads to losing valuable international talent.

How Do We Reduce These Errors?¶

To ensure our model performs well across both classes (Certified and Denied), we:

  1. Use F1 Score for Evaluation

    • Accuracy can be misleading when classes are imbalanced.
    • F1 Score balances Precision and Recall:
      • Precision: Out of predicted Certified cases, how many were actually Certified?
      • Recall: Out of all actual Certified cases, how many did the model correctly identify?
    • The F1 Score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall, which ensures the model isn’t performing well in just one and poorly in the other.

  2. Apply Balanced Class Weights

    • This tells the model to give equal attention to both Certified and Denied cases, even if one class appears much more frequently than the other.

Using the F1 Score and balanced class weights helps us minimize the impact of both false positives and false negatives, making the model fairer and more effective.

In [77]:
# Lets create method to calculare model performancce
# Accuracy, Precision, Recall and F1-score

def model_performance_metrics(
    model, predictors, target
):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # checking which probabilities are greater than threshold
    pred_temp = model.predict(predictors)
    # rounding off the above values to get classes
    pred = np.round(pred_temp)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )
    return df_perf

def calculate_confusion_matrix(model, predictors, target):
    
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)

    # Labels: TN, FP, FN, TP with count and % format
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["True Negative\n{0}\n{1:.2%}".format(cm[0, 0], cm[0, 0] / cm.sum()),
             "False Positive\n{0}\n{1:.2%}".format(cm[0, 1], cm[0, 1] / cm.sum())],
            ["False Negative\n{0}\n{1:.2%}".format(cm[1, 0], cm[1, 0] / cm.sum()),
             "True Positive\n{0}\n{1:.2%}".format(cm[1, 1], cm[1, 1] / cm.sum())]
        ]
    )

    # Plot
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 4))
    for i in range(2):
        for j in range(2):
            ax.add_patch(plt.Rectangle((j, i), 1, 1, fill=False, edgecolor='black', lw=2))
            ax.text(j + 0.5, i + 0.5, labels[i, j],
                    ha="center", va="center", fontsize=12, color="black")

    # Add outer border around entire matrix
    ax.add_patch(plt.Rectangle((0, 0), 2, 2, fill=False, edgecolor='black', lw=3))

    # Axes formatting
    ax.set_xticks([0.5, 1.5])
    ax.set_xticklabels(["Pred: 0", "Pred: 1"])
    ax.set_yticks([0.5, 1.5])
    ax.set_yticklabels(["True: 0", "True: 1"])
    ax.invert_yaxis()
    ax.set_xlim(0, 2)
    ax.set_ylim(0, 2)
    ax.set_title("Confusion Matrix", fontsize=14)
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Function to evaluate and collect performance
def evaluate_models_on_given_data(models, X_eval, y_eval):
    """Evaluate pre-trained models on a given dataset (e.g. validation/test)"""
    performance = {}
    for name, model in models.items():
        df = model_performance_metrics(model, X_eval, y_eval)
        performance[name] = df.iloc[0]
    return pd.DataFrame(performance).T

Model Evaluation Summary¶

To compare different classification models for predicting visa approval status, I evaluated five ensemble methods using four key metrics: Accuracy, Recall, Precision, and F1 Score and computed these metrics on both the training and validation datasets.

Observations from Training Performance:¶

  • Bagging performed very well on training data with high precision and recall, indicating strong generalization.
  • Random Forest achieved perfect performance on training data (100% for all metrics), which suggests overfitting — the model memorized the training set.
  • AdaBoost and Gradient Boosting had lower training performance, which is expected as they are more regularized and conservative learners.
  • XGBoost performed well, striking a good balance between high recall and high precision, without overfitting.

Observations from Validation Performance:¶

  • Bagging showed an F1 score of ~0.77 on validation (vs. ~0.99 on training), indicating moderate overfitting, but still decent generalization.
  • Random Forest dropped from a perfect F1 of 1.0 on training to ~0.80 on validation — this suggests strong overfitting, despite acceptable validation performance.
  • AdaBoost and Gradient Boosting had very similar F1 scores on both training and validation (~0.82), which indicates they are generalizing well and are less prone to overfitting.
  • XGBoost had a validation F1 of ~0.81 (vs. ~0.90 on training), showing some overfitting, but it still maintained strong performance.

Key Takeaways:¶

  • Bagging and XGBoost are the best-performing models in terms
  • AdaBoost, Gradient Boosting, and XGBoost showed the most balanced performance between training and validation, suggesting good generalization.
  • Bagging performed well but showed a noticeable drop in F1 from training to validation, indicating moderate overfitting.
  • Random Forest achieved perfect scores on training but dropped significantly on validation, pointing to clear overfitting (not data leakage).
  • F1 Score was chosen as the primary evaluation metric because it balances both types of errors:
    • Type I Error (False Positives) – predicting "Certified" when it should be "Denied"
    • Type II Error (False Negatives) – predicting "Denied" when it should be "Certified"

# Apply SMOTE

# sampling_strategy=1:
#   This sets the ratio of minority to majority class after resampling.
#   A value of 1 means the minority class will be oversampled to match the majority class exactly (1:1 ratio).

# k_neighbors=5:
#   This defines the number of nearest neighbors used to generate synthetic samples.
#   For each minority class sample, SMOTE finds its 5 nearest neighbors and creates new points between them.

# random_state=1:
#   Sets the seed for random number generation to ensure reproducibility.
#   Using the same seed means you'll get the same resampling results each time you run the code.

sm = SMOTE(sampling_strategy=1, k_neighbors=5, random_state=1)
X_train_over_sampled_data, y_train_over_sampled_data = sm.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

Model Building - Undersampled Data¶

Undersampling the Training Data¶

We use RandomUnderSampler from imblearn to handle class imbalance by reducing the size of the majority class.

  • The fit_resample() method creates a new training set where the number of samples from each class is equal.
  • This helps avoid model bias toward the majority class.
  • Unlike SMOTE (which adds data), undersampling removes real data, so it’s best used when the dataset is large enough.

Hyperparameter Tuning - Random Forest¶

In [93]:
%%time
# measures the execution time of the entire code cell

# random_state=1: ensures reproducibility
# oob_score=True: enables out-of-bag score estimation (an internal validation score, like cross-validation)
# uses bootstrapped samples to train individual trees (standard in RF).

rfc_tuned = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=1, oob_score=True, bootstrap=True)

# searching over 2×2×3×3 = 36 combinations of parameters

parameters = {
    "max_depth": list(np.arange(5, 15, 5)), # [5, 10]
    "max_features": ["sqrt", "log2"], # number of features to consider at each split
    "min_samples_split": [3, 5, 7], # minimum samples required to split a node
    "n_estimators": np.arange(10, 40, 10), # number of trees: [10, 20, 30]
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
# custom scoring function that GridSearchCV can use to evaluate each combination of hyperparameters
# using F1 score instead of default accuracy
# to balance precision and recall, ideal for imbalanced datasets.
acc_scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.f1_score) 

# Run the grid search

#exhaustive search over all combinations in parameters.
# 5-fold cross-validation for each combination
#n_jobs=-1 runs it in parallel for speed

grid_obj = GridSearchCV(rfc_tuned, parameters, scoring=acc_scorer, cv=5, n_jobs=-1)

#Fits the grid search using the oversampled training data
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train_over_sampled_data, y_train_over_sampled_data)


# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
rfc_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_ # Extracts the best-performing model from the grid search.

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.

# it re-trains the best model on the original training data
# To generalize on natural distributions again.
rfc_tuned.fit(X_train, y_train)

  • High recall on both training (0.91) and validation (0.89) shows the model is highly effective at detecting the positive class (e.g., "Certified" visa cases).
    → This is important in applications where missing a true positive is costly.

  • Precision is slightly lower than recall, but still strong — suggesting some false positives, but within a reasonable margin.
    → This trade-off is acceptable when recall is more critical.

  • Accuracy is lower than F1, which often happens in imbalanced datasets.
    → Reinforces that F1 is the more appropriate metric to evaluate performance in this context.

Summary:¶

The tuned RandomForestClassifier is performing robustly, with excellent generalization, strong recall, and balanced precision.
This makes it a reliable model choice for imbalanced classification tasks like visa approval prediction.

%%time
# measures the execution time of the entire code cell

# random_state=1: ensures reproducibility
abc_tuned = AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=1)

# searching over 2×3×3 = 18 combinations of parameters

parameters = {
    # Let's try different max_depth for base_estimator
    "estimator": [
        DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=2, random_state=1),
        DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=3, random_state=1),
    ],
    "n_estimators": np.arange(50,110,25),
    "learning_rate": np.arange(0.01,0.1,0.05),
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
# custom scoring function that GridSearchCV can use to evaluate each combination of hyperparameters
# using F1 score instead of default accuracy
# to balance precision and recall, ideal for imbalanced datasets.
acc_scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.f1_score) 

# Run the grid search

#exhaustive search over all combinations in parameters.
# 5-fold cross-validation for each combination
#n_jobs=-1 runs it in parallel for speed

grid_obj = GridSearchCV(abc_tuned, parameters, scoring=acc_scorer, cv=5, n_jobs=-1)

#Fits the grid search using the oversampled training data
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)


# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
abc_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_ # Extracts the best-performing model from the grid search.

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.

# it re-trains the best model on the original training data
# To generalize on natural distributions again.
abc_tuned.fit(X_train, y_train)

Final Model Selection Based on Validation Performance¶

After comparing the performance of all tuned ensemble models across training and validation datasets, evaluation is based on the following:

Metric Importance:¶

  • F1 Score: Primary metric used due to imbalanced classes (Certified vs Denied).
  • Recall: Important for minimizing false negatives (i.e., missing Certified cases).
  • Precision: Ensures false positives (wrongly approving Denied cases) are controlled.
  • Accuracy: Less informative in imbalanced settings; used as a reference only.

Suggested/Propsed Final Decision:¶

  • Tuned AdaBoostClassifier is selected as the best-performing model.
  • It achieved the highest validation F1 score (0.8281).
  • Demonstrated excellent generalization with the smallest train–validation gap.
  • Balanced both precision and recall effectively.
